Sid:

To see the Quikscript you have to log on to Read_Alphabet.  Go to fon=
t section and download the Jerome.ttf font.  Keep track of where you downlo=
ad it on your computer.  Once the download is complete, use Windows explore=
r to go to the spot where the download is saved.  Copy the file (Jerome.ttf=
) and paste it in your windows fonts directory (folder).

When this is done=
 successfully, your list of fonts will include Jerome.  It will be availabl=
e to your word processor or to Wordpad.  When I was using Windows 98, I occ=
asionally had a little problem getting it to work with my browser.  The Qui=
kscript characters are set up the same as the Shavian fonts are on the keyb=
oard.  To be able to type messages in Quikscript, you have to learn the pos=
ition of the letters.  

We are currently discussing a remapping of the Qui=
kscript character locations on the keyboard to make them easier, i.e. more =
logical, to learn.  In addition to the Quikscript version of the Shavian ch=
aracters, Jerome also has the half-letters and alternate letters which Read=
 added to Quikscript, plus the characters which Jon Zuck refers to as &quot;liga=
tures&quot; by which he mean the characters combining a vowel followed by an &quot;r.=
&quot;


Paige
